USER   GROUP   OTHERS
rwx    r-x     r-x
First 3 = owner permissions
Next 3 = group permissions
Last 3 = others permissions
How does a normal user change a password without root permission?
Because of SUID.

SUID (Set user ID)--> When a file with SUID is executed, it runs with the permissions of the fileâ€™s OWNER, not the user who runs it. 
        Purpose: Allow normal users to run specific commands that require higher (owner/root) privileges.
        rwsr-xr-x
          ^
          â€˜sâ€™ in the user (owner) execute position
numeric code: 4xxx
Set SUID: chmod 4755 file
Remove SUID: chmod u-s file
Instead of r w x, we see r w s.

Meaning of that s:

When ANYONE runs this file (normal user),
the system temporarily gives them the ownerâ€™s identity.

SGID (Set Group ID) --> For Files & Directories , File executes with the groupâ€™s permissions, not the userâ€™s group.
rwxr-sr-x
      ^
      â€˜sâ€™ in group execute position
Numeric Code: 2xxx
            All files created inside the directory automatically inherit the directoryâ€™s group.
Purpose: Ensures team collaboration inside shared directories.
Set SGID: chmod 2755 folder
Remove SGID: chmod g-s folder
Shared team folder:  /projects/devops/
                      Every file created inside will belong to group devops.
Sticky Bit â€”> For Directories Only, Inside a directory with Sticky Bit, users can delete only their own files, even if they have write permission.
Purpose: Protects files in shared directories.
Symbol in permissions:
drwxrwxrwt
         ^
         â€˜tâ€™ in others execute position
Numeric Code:1xxx
Set Sticky Bit:
                  chmod 1755 folder
Remove Sticky Bit:
                  chmod o-t folder
Real Example:
            /tmp directory in Linux:
drwxrwxrwt
Everyone can write, but cannot delete each other's files.
| Feature        | Works On            | Symbol           | Numeric  | Meaning                          |
| -------------- | ------------------- | ---------------- | -------- | -------------------------------- |
| **SUID**       | Files               | s in user slot   | **4xxx** | Run as file **owner**            |
| **SGID**       | Files & Directories | s in group slot  | **2xxx** | Run as **group** / Inherit group |
| **Sticky Bit** | Directories         | t in others slot | **1xxx** | Only owner can delete own files  |

sudo (Superuser DO)
ðŸ”¹ A command that allows a normal user to run specific commands as root (or another user) temporarily.
sudo command
The system checks if you are listed in /etc/sudoers file.
If yes â†’ you can run that command as root without switching user. sudo requires your own password (not root password).
eg. sudo chown username ownership.txt       >> is se hum owner ko temporary change kr paenge
    sudo chown :groupname ownership_folder  >> is se hum group ko temporary change kr paenge
    sudo chown -R :developers ownership_folder >>-R â†’ recursive (applies to all files/subfolders).
Change both user and group at once
   sudo chown rahul:developers ownership.txt
   Owner â†’ rahul
   Group â†’ developers

APT = Advanced Package Tool
ðŸ‘‰ APT ka use kiske liye hota hai?
        Software install karne ke liye
        Software update karne ke liye
        Dependencies download karne ke liye
        Packages remove karne ke liye

Common APT commands
        sudo apt update      # repositories refresh/update
        sudo apt upgrade     # new versions install
        sudo apt install nginx
        sudo apt remove nginx
        sudo apt search nginx
